        <!-- Toronto high school overview -->
        <h2 class="mb-2">High School in Toronto: Your Options</h2>
        <p>
          In Toronto, every student is assigned a <strong>home school</strong> within either the <strong>TDSB</strong> (Toronto District School Board) or the <strong>TCDSB</strong> (Toronto Catholic District School Board) based on their home address — and they're guaranteed a spot there. But Grade 8 students have up to <strong>four different ways</strong> to start high school:
        </p>
        <div class="info-box info-box-teal mt-1 mb-2">
          <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:auto 1fr;gap:.4rem .75rem;font-size:.9rem">
            <span>🏫</span><span><strong>Local Home School</strong> — your designated neighbourhood school, no application required</span>
            <span>🎨</span><span><strong>Specialized Program</strong> — arts, IB, STEM, French Immersion, or sports at a specific school (application required)</span>
            <span>🗺️</span><span><strong>Out of Area Transfer</strong> — attend a regular school outside your catchment (board application required)</span>
            <span>🧠</span><span><strong>Gifted / Enrichment</strong> — congregated gifted class for formally identified students (IPRC process required)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>
          All four options lead to the same credential — the <strong>Ontario Secondary School Diploma (OSSD)</strong> — and all four keep every post-secondary pathway open to you, depending on your course choices in Grades 9–12. Both TDSB and TCDSB schools offer the full Ontario curriculum.
        </p>

        <!-- Specialized programs explained -->
        <h2 id="specialized" class="mb-2 mt-3">Specialized Programs: What Are They?</h2>
        <p>
          Specialized programs are offered at <strong>designated schools</strong> within each school board and focus on a specific area: Visual Arts, Music, Drama, Dance, Media Arts, Technology/STEM, International Baccalaureate (IB), Extended French, French Immersion, or Elite Sports.
        </p>
        <p>
          Students from across the city travel to attend these programs. Because everyone is there for the same reason, the peer community is often especially strong. Most programs require an <strong>application, audition, portfolio, or academic assessment</strong>.
        </p>
        <div class="info-box info-box-amber">
          <strong>⏰ Key dates:</strong> TDSB and TCDSB open specialized program applications in <strong>November or December</strong> and close them in <strong>January or February</strong> of your Grade 8 year. TDSB: tdsb.on.ca · TCDSB: tcdsb.org
        </div>

        <!-- Out of area explained -->
        <h2 id="outofarea" class="mb-2 mt-3">Out of Area Transfers: How Do They Work?</h2>
        <p>
          An <strong>out-of-area transfer</strong> (also called a boundary transfer or non-resident transfer) allows you to request enrollment at a school that isn't your designated home school — without needing to be in a specialized program.
        </p>
        <p>Common reasons for an out-of-area request:</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom:1rem">
          <li>A sibling already attends that school</li>
          <li>The school is closer to a parent/guardian's workplace</li>
          <li>A specific sport team, club, or elective is only available at that school</li>
          <li>The school's culture or community feels like a better fit</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <strong>Important:</strong> Out-of-area approvals are <em>not guaranteed</em>. They depend on available space at the receiving school. Contact <strong>TDSB Student Support Services</strong> or the <strong>TCDSB Student Placement office</strong> in <strong>January–March</strong> of Grade 8 to apply.
        </p>

        <!-- Gifted/IPRC explained -->
        <h2 id="gifted" class="mb-2 mt-3">Gifted Programs: The IPRC Process</h2>
        <p>
          Both TDSB and TCDSB Gifted programs require <strong>formal identification</strong> through the <strong>Identification, Placement and Review Committee (IPRC)</strong> process, managed by each board's Special Education department. Here's how it works:
        </p>
        <ol style="margin-bottom:1rem">
          <li><strong>Request a referral</strong> — Ask your school's principal or vice-principal to refer you (or your child) for a psycho-educational assessment. Parents can also request this.</li>
          <li><strong>Psycho-educational assessment</strong> — A registered psychologist administers tests (including IQ assessments) to measure cognitive strengths. This can take 1–2 sessions.</li>
          <li><strong>IPRC meeting</strong> — The committee (principal, teacher, special education staff, and parents) reviews the results and decides on identification.</li>
          <li><strong>Identification</strong> — If identified as "Gifted," your child is placed in a congregated gifted class at a designated school or receives enrichment support at their home school.</li>
          <li><strong>IEP</strong> — An Individual Education Plan is created to support the student's specific learning needs.</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="info-box info-box-teal">
          <strong>⏰ Start early:</strong> The IPRC process can take <strong>2–3 months</strong>. Request a referral in September or October of Grade 8 to meet high school placement timelines.
        </div>

        <!-- Open house tips -->
        <h2 id="openhouse" class="mb-2 mt-3">Open House Tips</h2>
        <p>Most Toronto TDSB and TCDSB high schools hold Open Houses between <strong>November and January</strong>. These events are free, open to students and parents, and are your best chance to:</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom:1rem">
          <li>See the school building, facilities, and classrooms</li>
          <li>Talk to current students and ask honest questions</li>
          <li>Meet teachers from the program you're interested in</li>
          <li>Pick up application forms and deadline information</li>
          <li>Get a feel for the school's culture and community</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="info-box info-box-amber">
          <strong>Pro tip:</strong> Write down your questions before you go. Ask students — not just teachers — what they honestly think of the school.
        </div>

        <!-- About the tool -->
        <h2 id="tool" class="mb-2 mt-3">About Find your Highschool</h2>
        <p>
          Find your Highschool is a free, independent tool built to help Grade 8 students and their families explore Toronto high school options within TDSB and TCDSB. It is <strong>not affiliated with the TDSB, TCDSB, or the Ontario Ministry of Education</strong>.
        </p>
        <div class="info-box info-box-amber">
          <strong>⚠️ Disclaimer:</strong> This tool is for <em>exploration and reflection only</em>. Always verify application requirements, deadlines, and school-specific details directly with your school board. Information may change year to year.
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <h2 id="faq" class="mt-3 mb-2">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            What if I don't get into the specialized program I applied for?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            You'll still attend your designated home school — your spot is guaranteed there. Many students who didn't get into their first-choice program discover they love their home school. Some students also try reapplying in Grade 10 for programs that accept mid-high school applicants.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            Can I change schools after Grade 9 if I'm unhappy?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Yes, in most cases. You can transfer to a new school mid-year or for the start of a new school year. If you're in a specialized program and want to leave, contact your school's guidance counselor — transferring back to your home school or another school is usually possible. Some specialized programs, however, require re-audition or reapplication.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            How do I find out which schools are in my catchment area?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Use the TDSB School Locator at tdsb.on.ca or visit tcdsb.org to find your designated schools. Enter your home address and it will show your assigned elementary and secondary school. TDSB serves Toronto's public school students; TCDSB serves Toronto's Catholic school students (a baptismal certificate may be required).
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            Do specialized programs cost money?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            The programs themselves are free — they're part of the TDSB or TCDSB public school system. However, there may be costs associated with materials, instruments, uniforms (for sports programs), or TTC transit (since the school may be across the city). Ask the school about any expected program fees at their Open House.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            What if I think I might be gifted but I've never been tested?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Talk to your school's principal or a parent/guardian. Any teacher, parent, or principal can request an IPRC referral for a psycho-educational assessment. You don't need to already be identified — that's what the assessment is for. Start the conversation in September of Grade 8 to allow enough time.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            Can I be in a specialized program AND apply for an out-of-area transfer?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Specialized program applications and out-of-area transfers are separate processes. If you get into a specialized program, you'd attend that school under the program (not as an out-of-area student). If you want to attend a school outside your catchment for reasons other than a specialized program, that's when you'd apply for an out-of-area transfer.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')" tabindex="0" role="button" aria-expanded="false">
            Does going to a specialized program affect which university I can get into?
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Not directly — Ontario universities look at your Grade 11/12 marks and course choices, not which Toronto school you attended. However, specialized programs often provide better preparation in their area (e.g., an arts portfolio, IB credentials, or a STEM background), which can strengthen university applications for related programs.
          </div>
        </div>

